<subSubSection id="E7BC57115B79B8F9F0C82909A286067F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="F0AF64978E38EA14AF80E1D80A74155B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DBD22ABF87B79B9E3FAAD82E048B1BC1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The species is named after Dr Jiri 
<normalizedToken id="07CB366245AE67962DA36D5942CFAD0D" originalValue="Hájek">Hajek</normalizedToken>
for collecting the specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="76A7F3189F793AD71939715CF4E2FE76" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DD7EA7D0F7701348A3ED4BA189C04A67" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="390EC92C7BCF7D0D50123DF479CD9C40" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">China (Yunnan).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B894FAA23389678E8633D13A7EEF2D2E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="0FB997445C4604B6AEAFABBEAB4046F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ACBD416A9BE016DD1346EFFEB8B9C3B6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
See ecology of 
<taxonomicName id="7007FE9AE8CBCE9309942F7492435830" authorityName="Wang &amp; Li &amp; Li" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Neoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neoperla gaoligongshana" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gaoligongshana">
<emphasis id="30962DCF089DA9F0C5EDE0189F892803" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Neoperla gaoligongshana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95762612BBBFD11529CCD2E105AFFDFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="426571CED0BB13756059AACA788881BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B21D7D36924D563937CC7D82E1EB957C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species is a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="500E8ACAD2A4D1ABF054018E8E0E5F5D" class="Insecta" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. clymene" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clymene">
<emphasis id="E67D5BD1AFC439F41AAB39C241998578" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">N. clymene</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Color pattern, pronotum, and male genital features are similar to 
<taxonomicName id="9FEA3C8277913E78ACAD6F93476907FB" authorityName="Stark &amp; Sivec" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Neoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neoperla orissa" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orissa">
<emphasis id="CBF04C2712945C26D3F9C4D7C0592483" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Neoperla orissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stark &amp; Sivec, 2015 from India. The new species can be easily separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4DBA06E805301B9C2820A1291FA2C649" class="Insecta" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. orissa" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orissa">
<emphasis id="453841CB8028E303A3B36CB1915A3869" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">N. orissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the projection of tergum 7 and detail of the aedeagal sac armature. In 
<taxonomicName id="624D2546D716A5524EACB4E5F2E5AC2E" class="Insecta" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. hajeki" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hajeki">
<emphasis id="2E1F9195C986D3D033C6BCE9DEA4686F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">N. hajeki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the projection of tergum 7 is pointed in dorsal aspect, and the dorsal spines of the aedeagal sac are triangularly arranged. In 
<taxonomicName id="E28DE7ED27509FB570A2AE4377CC58E9" class="Insecta" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. orissa" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orissa">
<emphasis id="341119F59294FBE7C713A7C791EBC565" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">N. orissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the slender and median projection of tergum 7 appears truncate in dorsal aspect, and the spines of the sac are arranged in several close-set rows.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
